          "body": "Caleb's speech in verses 6–11 is the longest personal testimony in the distribution section of Joshua. He does not open with his request — he opens with God's word: 'You know the word which the LORD spoke to Moses... concerning you and me' (14:6). The rhetorical sequence matters. Before Caleb names what he wants, he names what God said. His entire claim rests on a specific divine utterance, not on his own merit or tenure. He testifies in sequence: I was forty years old (v. 7), I brought an honest report (v. 7), my brothers melted the people's hearts with fear (v. 8), I followed YHWH fully (v. 8), Moses swore an oath (v. 9), and YHWH has kept me alive for forty-five years just as He spoke (v. 10). Each step in the testimony is anchored in a divine action — speaking, swearing, keeping alive. Caleb is not presenting his own résumé; he is presenting evidence of God's reliability. His vitality at eighty-five (v. 11) is, in this framework, itself a divine testimony: YHWH has preserved this man for this moment."
