          "title": "The request: claiming the hardest territory by faith",
          "body": "Verse 12 is the chapter's theological summit. 'Now then, give me this hill country about which the LORD spoke on that day, for you heard on that day that Anakim were there, with great fortified cities; perhaps the LORD will be with me, and I will drive them out as the LORD has spoken.' Three features of this request demand sustained attention. First, Caleb asks for the hardest territory. The Anakim are the giants whose sight caused the ten spies to describe themselves as grasshoppers (Numbers 13:33) — the very people who generated the cowardice that condemned a generation to the wilderness. Caleb deliberately chooses that contested ground, not a settled valley. Second, the word 'perhaps' (*ulay* in Hebrew) is not the hedge of a wavering faith — it is the theological modesty of a man who knows the battle belongs to YHWH and will not presume to guarantee its outcome. It is Caleb's way of saying: I am confident in the promise; I do not command the promiser. Third, the grounding is entirely backward-looking: 'as the LORD has spoken.' Caleb's confidence is not in his own strength (though he claims it in v. 11) but in the prior speech of God. This is faith in its precise biblical definition: the substance of things hoped for, grounded in the word of the One who cannot lie."
