          "body": "Joshua's response in verses 13–14 is undelayed, unqualified, and interpretively decisive. He blesses Caleb and gives him Hebron — not after deliberation, not after consulting the tribal heads, because no consultation is needed. The oath of Moses is sufficient warrant. The narrator then renders the theological verdict in verse 14: 'Hebron became the inheritance of Caleb the son of Jephunneh the Kenizzite until this day, because he followed the LORD God of Israel fully.' The word 'because' (*yaan*) is the interpretive key. This is not a grant of charity or seniority — it is the covenant consequence of covenantal faithfulness. Full-hearted following (*male achar*) produces full inheritance. The same phrase used by Caleb to describe his own conduct (v. 8), invoked in Moses's oath (v. 9), is now the narrator's own evaluation (v. 14, twice). The repetition is deliberate and emphatic: three independent witnesses — Caleb himself, the Mosaic oath, and the inspired narrator — agree on both the fact and the ground of the inheritance."
