          "body": "Verse 15 is brief but theologically loaded. Hebron's former name was Kiriath-arba — 'city of Arba' — and Arba was 'the greatest man among the Anakim.' The naming note is the narrator's final act of covenant irony: the city named for the greatest of the giants, the very giants who made ten spies lose their faith and an entire generation lose their inheritance, becomes the permanent possession of the one man who never flinched. The chapter closes with the refrain 'then the land had rest from war' — shaqat milchamah — a phrase Joshua uses at key campaign conclusions (cf. Joshua 11:23; 21:44; 23:1). Its placement here ties Caleb's personal grant to the broader pacification of the land and signals that the covenant promises are not merely spiritual but territorial, historical, and geopolitically concrete. YHWH's word does not float above history — it lands in it, renames cities, displaces giants, and grants rest."
