        "excerpt": "by the lot of their inheritance, as the LORD commanded through Moses, for the nine tribes and the half-tribe.",
        "body": "The opening framework (vv. 1–5) is frequently treated as throat-clearing before the Caleb narrative, but it carries the chapter's first interpretive claim: the land distribution is not Israel's administrative achievement but YHWH's covenantal fulfillment. The mechanism of the lot (*goral*, v. 2) is a standard ancient Near Eastern allocation procedure — but Proverbs 16:33 makes the Israelite theology of it explicit: 'The lot is cast into the lap, but its every decision is from the LORD.' The lot does not reduce YHWH to a random number generator; it removes human favoritism from the equation while preserving His sovereign direction of outcome.\n\nThe double reference to 'as the LORD commanded through Moses' (vv. 2, 5) is crucial for reading the entire distribution section. Joshua and Eleazar are executing a commission given to Moses in the Pentateuch (Numbers 26:52–56; 33:54; 34:13–15). This is obedience to prior revelation, not improvisation. The entire nine-and-a-half tribe allotment rests on the authority of the Mosaic commission — meaning Joshua 13–21 is, in canonical terms, the Book of Numbers finding its completion.\n\nThe Levitical exemption (vv. 3–4) makes the same point from a different angle. Levi receives no territorial inheritance because YHWH Himself is Levi's inheritance (Numbers 18:20; Deuteronomy 10:9). The tribe consecrated entirely to the service of the sanctuary does not receive what the other tribes receive — it receives the One the other tribes serve. This is not a deprivation but an elevation: Levi's portion is not less than Benjamin's or Dan's, it is categorically different and categorically greater. The chapter's opening framework thus holds two covenant truths in tension: YHWH gives the land by sovereign direction through the lot, and He reserves the right to give Himself rather than land to the tribe He has most fully claimed.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Goral* (lot, v. 2) is elsewhere used of the lot cast for the two goats on the Day of Atonement (Leviticus 16:8–10) — divine determination at the holiest moment of the year. *Tsavah* (commanded, vv. 2, 5) is the standard Pentateuchal word for Mosaic commission; its double use here brackets the entire allotment section as obedience to prior divine instruction."
