        "number": 3,
        "title": "The boldness of the eighty-five-year-old — faith that requests the Anakim's fortress",
        "range": "14:10-12",
        "excerpt": "Now then, give me this hill country about which the LORD spoke on that day, for you heard on that day that Anakim were there, with great fortified cities.",
        "body": "Verses 10–12 are the chapter's theological climax. Caleb's claim to undiminished physical strength at eighty-five (v. 11) has two functions: it is a personal testimony to YHWH's preserving faithfulness (he is not merely alive but combat-ready), and it is the basis on which he makes his request in verse 12. He is not asking for a comfortable retirement allotment proportionate to his age — he is asking for the hardest available territory.\n\nThe Anakim are Joshua's most fearsome remaining opponents. They are the giants whose sight at Kadesh caused ten spies to describe the Israelite army as grasshoppers (Numbers 13:33). Joshua 11:21–22 records that Joshua had already cut off the Anakim from the highlands of Judah and Israel — but remnants remained in Gaza, Gath, and Ashdod, and Hebron itself still needed to be secured at the personal level Caleb is now claiming. Caleb's request for Hebron is therefore not a nostalgic longing for a promised plot — it is an aggressive act of warfare-faith. He volunteers for the hardest assignment on the board precisely because it is where the giants live.\n\nThe word 'perhaps' (*ulay*, v. 12) has been misread as uncertainty about whether God will keep His promise. It is not. Caleb has just spent six verses establishing that God always keeps His promises. *Ulay* here is the modesty of a man who knows the battle belongs to YHWH and will not presume to turn a divine promise into a human guarantee of outcome. D. A. Carson's language for this kind of faith is apt: it is the faith that 'holds the promise with open hands,' trusting the promiser rather than managing the mechanism. Charles Spurgeon observes that Caleb does not say 'I will drive them out because I am strong' — he says 'perhaps the LORD will be with me.' The strength of verse 11 and the modesty of verse 12 belong together: strong enough to fight, humble enough to know who wins.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ulay* (perhaps, v. 12) — a particle of contingency that consistently marks appropriate human deference to divine sovereignty in the Old Testament (cf. Genesis 16:2; 1 Samuel 6:5; 2 Samuel 16:12). It never expresses doubt about God's character but about the human speaker's ability to predict how divine sovereignty will operate in a specific event. *Yarash* (drive out, v. 12) — the conquest verb: to dispossess, to take possession by force. Its use here echoes the Deuteronomy commission (Deuteronomy 9:3) and the Joshua 1 charge (Joshua 1:11). Caleb is not requesting a retirement plot; he is enlisting for a campaign."
