        "excerpt": "Therefore, Hebron became the inheritance of Caleb the son of Jephunneh the Kenizzite until this day, because he followed the LORD God of Israel fully.",
        "body": "Joshua's response in verse 13 is immediate and unqualified: he blessed Caleb and gave him Hebron. The blessing (*barakh*) is not merely ceremonial — it is the formal, priestly-judicial confirmation of a covenant transfer. Joshua does not question the claim, convene a committee, or subject the request to the same lot-casting used for the other tribes. The oath of Moses (v. 9) functions as the sufficient legal warrant. The speed and certainty of the grant signals that in covenant jurisprudence, the word of God spoken through His servant carries immediate binding authority.\n\nThe narrator's verdict in verse 14 is the chapter's interpretive keystone. 'Therefore, Hebron became the inheritance of Caleb... because he followed the LORD God of Israel fully.' The *therefore-because* construction is the narrator's explicit statement of the chapter's theology: Caleb's inheritance is a covenant consequence, not a gift of grace divorced from faithfulness. This does not introduce works-righteousness — the entire apparatus of Caleb's claim rests on God's prior promise (v. 9) and YHWH's preservation (v. 10), not on Caleb's accumulated virtue. But it does insist that full-hearted following has real covenant consequences in the economy of YHWH's dealings with His people. The inheritance was promised because Caleb followed fully (Numbers 14:24); the inheritance is granted because Caleb followed fully (Joshua 14:14). The phrase brackets the forty-five years.\n\nVerse 15's renaming note is the narrator's final theological comment. Kiriath-arba — 'city of Arba,' named for the greatest of the Anakim — becomes Hebron, the city of Caleb's covenant inheritance. The giant's name is displaced by the covenant man's possession. The closing refrain 'the land had rest from war' (*shaqat milchamah*) connects Caleb's personal grant to the macroscopic peace the conquest is achieving. Reformed commentators from Calvin onward have read this rest-motif as a typological pointer to the eschatological rest of Hebrews 4:1–11 — the pattern of YHWH giving conquest-rest to the faithful as a shadow of the ultimate rest His people will enter. Peter Davids's NIGTC work on Hebrews, alongside Moo's canonical instincts, reinforces this: every instance of Israel entering rest in Joshua participates in the theological grammar that Hebrews will make explicit. The land rests because the giants yield; the final rest will come when every enemy of Christ has been made His footstool (1 Corinthians 15:25–26).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Barakh* (blessed, v. 13) — the priestly-judicial blessing that formally ratifies a covenant transfer; the same root used of Melchizedek blessing Abraham (Genesis 14:19) and Isaac blessing Jacob (Genesis 27:27–29). *Shaqat* (rest, v. 15) — undisturbed peace, the absence of hostile pressure; a key verb in the Deuteronomistic theology of conquest-fulfillment. Its placement after Caleb's personal grant signals that even the micro-narrative of one man's inheritance participates in the macro-narrative of YHWH giving His people the covenant land."
